3905e3ea0343c56af6ebb76c0c8f990e.filed_by: City and County of San Francisco
3905e3ea0343c56af6ebb76c0c8f990e.description: SUMMARY:  On July 25, 2018, Richard Chien, Senior Program Specialist with the Department of the Environment, the City and County of San Francisco, attended an online meeting (webinar) hosted by the Pacific Coast Collaborative (PCC), of which San Francisco is a member. The post-presentation discussion was attended by Forest Kaser, advisor to Cmmr. Picker.  Mr. Chien, referring to the three-prong test for fuel substitution programs in this proceeding, stated that the Commission is reviewing the three-pronged test, and that currently, the test generally prevents the use of ratepayer funds to support “fuel substitution” measures, which affects the City’s plans to reduce carbon emissions including from use of fossil fuels for thermal end uses, such as water heating. San Francisco did not make any requests or recommendations with regard to the three-prong test.

36e03f1d1fa81b213c6ea909aa9b308d.description: Marin Clean Energy (MCE) noticed an oral ex-parte communication that occurred on October 6, 2016 at approximately 11:40 a.m., at the California Public Utilities Commission offices.  The communication was initiated by MCE.  The communication was between Beckie Menten, MCE Director of Customer Programs, and David Gamson, Chief Advisor to Commissioner Peterman, and lasted approximately 30 minutes.  Ms. Menten discussed Decision 16-08-019, the role of Community Choice Aggregator’s (CCAs) in the context of the new statewide and third party programs.  Ms. Menten also sought guidance on attribution for statewide programs, specifically, how to determine the share apportioned to CCAs due to an inconsistency in the Decision. Ms. Menten also discussed MCE’s proposals for the downstream pilots.

a15776597d40831f85010c9b64d524ea.description: SUMMARY: On March 23, 2016, Beckie Menten, Director of Customer Programs, Marin Clean Energy (MCE), met with Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, in San Francisco.  Also present was Mike Callahan-Dudley, Regulatory Counsel, MCE. Menten touched upon MCE’s recently filed Petition for Modification that requested an increase to its annual budget to account for MCE's Menten explained that the request indicated a formulaic approach to increasing Energy Efficiency funding due to expansion of Community Choice Aggregator service territory. Menten also noted that MCE's service territory grew 30% in 2015 and will likely see similar growth in 2016.

7c42cdacf8c40eb80127c5c81c8ac764.description: SUMMARY:  LATE FILED. On March 15, 2016, Dennis Quinn, Chief Operating Officer of Joule Assets Inc. (Joule Assets), met with Cmmr. Peterman in San Francisco.  Also present were David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, and Mike Gordon, Chief Executive Officer of Joule Assets. Quinn provided an overview of Joule Assets and its role as manager of the Energy Reduction Asset (ERA) Fund, a private equity fund that invests in energy reduction solutions in small and medium commercial facilities, including energy efficiency.  Quinn highlighted the ERA Fund’s focus on performance-based solutions using M&V for each participating site. Quinn described how Joule Assets achieves deployment through development of a network of contractor and technology partners; incorporates best practices, such as ICP certification with its projects and incorporates investment-grade backed performance insurance for its portfolio of projects. Quinn noted that the ERA Fund is interested in investing in projects availing of the principles of both SB 350 and AB 802. Joule Assets stated that it has been actively involved in providing input as California Alternative Energy and Advanced Transportation Financing Authority develops credit enhancement programs to support further energy efficiency investment to meet the objectives of SB 350.  Quinn reinforced that timely measurement and verification and baseline methodology development will be key to AB 802 success. Quinn encouraged the Commission to let the market demonstrate that solutions exist today for success. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

cb62c0a96626866aeb0791384b111ff4.description: SUMMARY:  On March 16, 2016, Beckie Menten, Director of Customer Programs of Marin Clean Energy (MCE), met with Cmmr. Peterman in San Francisco.  Also present were David Gamson and Joanna Gubman, advisors to Cmmr. Peterman; and Shalini Swaroop, Regulatory and Legislative Counsel, for MCE.  Menten touched upon MCE’s recently filed Petition for Modification that requested an increase to its annual budget to account for MCE's inclusion of new communities. Menten noted that MCE's service territory grew 30% in 2015 and will likely see similar growth in 2016. Menten indicated that the EE Coordinating Committee is an impressive effort that merits a high level of engagement from all parties. Menten described the capacity challenges that are faced by small program administrators, and indicated that the staff of MCE may need to scale back engagement efforts with the EE Coordinating Committee. However, Menten did not believe this would cause concerns because as local government agencies, CCAs are already subject to a variety of rules related to transparency.  Menten voiced concerns on the methodology of ex ante review and indicated an open and transparent forum for saving estimate review offered by the Technical Forum would be a welcome change. Menten further emphasized having CPUC engagement early on in the process will improve both savings estimates and stakeholder engagement.

af0e7d035154db53bccd824112924382.description: SUMMARY:  On March 17, 2016, Beckie Menten, Director of Customer Programs of Marin Clean Energy (MCE), met with Matthew Tisdale, advisor to Cmmr. Florio, in San Francisco. Menten touched upon MCE’s recently filed Petition for Modification that requested an increase to its annual budget to account for MCE's inclusion of new communities. Menten noted that MCE's service territory grew 30% in 2015 and will likely see similar growth in 2016. Menten outlined the reasoning behind its proposal for default administrator status of energy efficiency, citing the need to achieve cost effective programs and the challenges experienced in joint implementation thus far.

cc39986f3d72f6bff95257eae42850c4.description: SUMMARY:  On March 15, 2016, Richard Counihan of Nest Labs, Inc. (Nest), met with Cmmr. Peterman in San Francisco.  Also present were Jeffrey Gleeson and Aaron Berndt of Nest. The Nest team provided an overview of Nest’s product line, including relevant energy services and programs. The Nest team highlighted work currently underway to study the energy efficiency savings associated with smart thermostats in California climate zones. The Nest team discussed how smart thermostats can not only achieve electric and gas efficiency goals but also help with demand response and time-of-use rates. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

On March 1, 2016, Michael Campbell, Branch Manager of the Office of Ratepayer Advocates (ORA), met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco.  Also present were Daniel Buch, analyst, and Zhen Zhang, attorney, for the ORA.  ORA representatives stated that information from the energy efficiency “To-Code” pilots ordered by Decision 14-10-046 is necessary for the Commission to make informed decision. ORA representatives stated its concern about the timely implementation of energy efficiency “To-Code” pilots and how the delay will impact Commission decisions.  ORA expressed concern that the Commission’s decisions will be too expansive given the energy efficiency goals of AB 802 without information from the energy efficiency “To-Code” pilots. ORA representatives urged the Commission to encourage timely completion of the pilots.

075ad662a08dca1c21bc86bfc559238b.description: SUMMARY:  On February 17th, 2016, Annette Beitel of the California Technical Forum Staff (Cal TF Staff) met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco. Also present were Pete Skala, Energy Efficiency Program Manager, and Alejandra Mejia, of Cal TF Staff.  Cal TF Staff discussed the work of the Cal TF and the group's Electronic Technical Reference Manual (eTRM) proposal. Beitel, Mejia and Skala discussed the need for closer collaboration between energy efficiency Commission Staff and the California Technical Forum during measure review and in preparation for full implementation of the eTRM. Beitel stated her commitment to working with Mr. Skala to produce a joint document on next steps for moving forward with the eTRM project. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

a846aa8360d6a2c47cc84151a9377fd2.description: SUMMARY:  On February 12, 2016, Cynthia Mitchell, consultant on energy efficiency matters to The Utility Reform Network (TURN), sent an email to an undisclosed distribution list. The email was received by Hayley Goodson, Staff Attorney at TURN, and included an attachment consisting of an article written by Mitchell and published in California CURRENT, a publication of CA Energy Circuit Inc. Mitchell's article provides her opinions on some of the energy efficiency baseline issues related to the implementation of Assembly Bill 802. Goodson asked Mitchell for her distribution list, and learned that Mitchell had circulated the article to Cmmrs. Florio, Peterman, Sandoval, and Randolph, and to Matthew Tisdale, advisor to Cmmr. Florio, David Gamson and Ehren Seybert, advisors to Cmmr. Peterman, Ditas Katague and Michael Colvin, advisors to Cmmr. Sandoval, and Rachel Peterson and Sean Simon, advisors to Cmmr. Randolph.  A copy of the written communication is attached to the notice. The notice explains TURN does not believe this communication qualifies as an ex parte communication and reports this communication out of an abundance of caution.

65e25daf4b4a9e8ed755b1217a20addf.description: SUMMARY: on January 26, 2016, Donald Gilligan, President of the National Association of Energy Service Companies (ESCO) met with Cmmr. Peterman in San Francisco. Also present were David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, and Mr. Sperberg and Mr. Mahoney of ESCO.  ESCO representatives discussed the application of AB 802 to energy efficiency (EE) programs. ESCO representatives said that they believe that AB 802 offers the Commission an historic opportunity to simplify the administration of California EE programs, which has become unnecessarily complex over the past ten years, particularly in the area of savings baselines and EM&V. Gilligan said that this complexity makes the California programs less effective than in other states.  ESCO participants provided examples of projects and programs which they believe are hindered by the current Title 24 and Industry Standard Practice baselines. The ESCO participants urged the Commission to address the issue of the workload of the Energy Division, and stated that the current workload can result in untimely delivery of key reports and a growing lag between the accelerating innovation in EE technology and the incorporation of these technologies into EE programs.  Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

04bdd0124429e18b68469b1d123c2b5a.description: SUMMARY:  On January 13, 2016, Lowell Chu, Senior Environmental Specialist, the Association of Bay Area Governments, on behalf of the San Francisco Bay Area Regional Energy Network (BayREN), met with Cmmr. Peterman at the Notre Dave Apartments and Casa Lucas, in San Francisco.  Also present were David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman; and Rinna Lopez, Environmental Specialist, and Imma De la Cruz, Assistant Environmental Specialist, for the San Francisco Department of the Environment. Chu, Lopez and De la Cruz provided a tour of the facilities and highlighted the successful installation of energy efficiency projects that occurred in them through BayREN’s Multifamily Building Enhancements Program and the San Francisco Energy Watch.

8a98c8d4ba6d37fd4fce99dbac429a78.description: SUMMARY:  On January 12, 2016, Ralph Cavanagh, Co-Director of  Energy Program of the Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC), met with Cmmr. Peterman in San Francisco.  Also present were David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman; and Lara Ettenson, Director of California Energy Efficiency Policy, Peter Miller, Senior Scientist, Sierra Martinez, Legal Director, California Energy Projects, and Merrian Borgeson, Senior Scientist, for NRDC.  NRDC discussed its recommendations for meeting the state’s goal of doubling energy efficiency. Cavanagh, Miller, and Ettenson spoke about the benefits of the California Technical Forum and upcoming launch of the Rolling Portfolio Energy Efficiency Coordinating Committee.  Borgeson addressed the need to update rules and processes to better allow Program Administrators to try new things. Martinez and Ettenson spoke of the opportunity to take a new look at the forthcoming potential study to see what is truly feasible out to the year 2030.

c6775cf76289f4f8f9a77800f5c645d0.description: SUMMARY:  On December 11, 2015, Tom Eckhart, Chief Executive Officer of UCONS, LLC, had a conference call with Cmmr. Peterman.  Also participating in the telephone conference were David Gamson and Joanne Gutman, advisors to Cmmr. Peterman, and Shani Taha, Executive Vice President of UCONS, LLC. Taha reminded the Commissioner of their meeting 2 years ago in which she and Eckhart reviewed the barriers facing low and moderate income ratepayers from receiving the best and most innovative conservation programs from other regions where they have been found cost effective and beneficial to these customers.  Taha noted a key element of their success in the northwest was the Regional Technical Forum which they believed would help California address M&V processes which needed to be reworked.  Eckhart shared his observations having served over the past year and a half on the CALTF.  Eckhart stated his concern that the CALTF did not have formal standing and having the CPUC to define technical and policy roles for the Energy Division and Commission representatives could be helpful.  Eckhart observed that without Commission feedback and participation out of state participation from volunteers and experts could diminish.

b61eac75f34b17af8d1ebbdfb3e89fb8.description: SUMMARY:  On October 29, 2015, Terry Fry, Senior Vice President, Nexant, Inc. (Nexant), met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco.  Also present were Mushtaq Ahmad, Senior Manager, Milena Usabiaga, Project Manager, and Jack Stoddard, attorney, for Nexant.  At the meeting, Nexant briefed on a staff disposition that would deny energy efficiency savings claimed for a Nexant industrial retrocommissioning project. Nexant explained that air compressor projects represent significant energy efficiency savings potential, and it is not industry standard practice to repair air leaks in air compressor systems unless the air compressors are not meeting the customer's end use needs. Nextant further explained that Title 24 is not triggered in this instance and that Staff's characterization of the air compressor project as a "to code" project was incorrect.  Nextant also stated that it is prohibited from communicating directly with staff regarding errors in the disposition; and that because Nexant is a third party implementer, and not the Program Administrator, there is no clear process for it to appeal or seek review of the staff disposition.

b418b8f01207a50fb7fabb57262a148d.description: SUMMARY:  On October 6, 2015, Lara Ettenson, Director of California Energy Efficiency Policy, the Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC), met with Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco. Also present Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, and Peter Miller, Senior Scientist, and Sierra Martinez, Legal Director, California Energy Projects, were also present.  NRDC representatives discussed the findings of NRDC and E2's recent California Energy Efficiency Report (available at the following link: http://www.nrdc.org/energy/ca-energy-efficiency-opportunity.asp).  Miller and Ettenson discussed the need to move away from the opaque, non-collaborative process of establishing energy-saving estimates toward a more effective process. Martinez discussed complementing efficiency programs with additional opportunities such as leveraging metered data and expanding request for offering (RFO) approaches to procure energy. Ettenson discussed the exciting prospects of the rolling portfolio and forthcoming stakeholder process for planning efficiency portfolios.

b0eda6c19bdb139dd91fa8d9ede8a8a6.description: SUMMARY:  On September 11 and 14, 2015, representatives of the California Energy Efficiency Industry Council (Efficiency Council) had several ex parte communications at the Commission.  The communications involved the same information.  On September 11, 2015, Margie Gardner, Executive Director of the Efficiency Council, met with Julie Fitch, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, and Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in two separate meetings in San Francisco.  At the meeting with Julie Fitch also present was Jennifer Kalafut, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, present at each meeting were Ted Pope, the Chairman, and Jim Kelsey, the Chair of the Custom Review Committee, for the Efficiency Council.  Gardner noted the importance of the need for a custom review process. Gardner stated that the Efficiency Council is concerned that the Commissioners have not fully considered the impact that the current dysfunctional process has had on customers and would like to see the Commission, the investor-owned utilities and energy efficiency program implementers work together to bring forward solutions to the issues before Phase III.  Gardner asked that the Proposed Decision on Phase II therefore include certain specific modifications. On September 14, 2015, Pope sent an e-mail to Julie Fitch, Scott Murtishaw, and Jennifer Kalafut. A copy of the e-mail is attached to the notice.

e6f94368507c6f9935a5f696cc93c046.description: SUMMARY:  On May 8, 2015, Hayley Goodson, Staff Attorney at The Utility Reform Network, met with Julie Fitch, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco.  Goodson discussed SB 765 (Wolk), which would require the Commission to contract with an independent entity to serve as the statewide administrator of energy efficiency market transformation initiatives. Goodson specifically discussed governance, oversight, and funding issues related to SB 765.  Goodson also briefly discussed potential changes to the Commission's policies on energy efficiency baselines. Goodson mentioned the importance of considering the totality of interrelated policies that should be revisited in conjunction with baselines, such as assumptions about savings from the Codes and Standards program and inputs into the demand forecast. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

SUMMARY:  On April 1, 2015, Anthony Harrison, Policy Director of the California Energy Efficiency Industry Council (Efficiency Council) met with Cmmr. Peterman.  Also present were Julie Fitch, Jennifer Kalafut and Melicia Charles, advisors to Cmmr. Peterman, and Ben Bodell, law student extern for Cmmr. Peterman; Jeanne Clinton, Governor's CPUC advisor on energy efficiency; and Steve Schiller, Board Chair Emeritus, for the Efficiency Council.  Efficiency Council's representatives discussed Assembly Bill 1330, a bill currently introduced in the  
California Legislature, which is sponsored by the Efficiency Council.  The Efficiency Council representatives explained that this legislation could work in conjunction with the goal setting process within the proceeding, as it simply establishes a "floor" by which energy savings through efficiency must be achieved.  Schiller explained that since energy efficiency is a resource that all Californians can benefit from, the Efficiency Council felt that it was important to ensure disadvantage communities were included in a major way in the state's energy efficiency efforts. A written material (attached to the notice) was used.

98a9edae8da834e7125c70b5fa91d734.description: [filed Pursuant to Rule 8.4 and the October 16, 2014 ruling in A.13-12-012.]  SUMMARY: On October 29, 2014, Randall Litteneker, Attorney, Pacific Gas and Electric (PG&E), and Dawn Weisz, Executive Officer, Marin Clean Energy (MCE), met with Gurbux Kahlon, William Maguire, Jean Lamming, Peter Skala, Hazlyn Fortune, Aloke Gupta, and Jonathan Tom of the Energy Division; and  Pouneh Ghaffarian and Mitchell Shapson of the Legal Division, in San Francisco.  On behalf of PG&E also present were Jan Berman, Senior Director, Customer Energy Solutions, Al Gaspari, Principal Program Manager, of Customer Energy Solutions; David Gutierrez, Principal of CCA Relations, of Customer Energy Solutions, and Sidney Dietz, Director of Regulatory Relations; and on behalf of MCE - Elizabeth Kelly, Legal Director; and Beckie Menten, Energy Efficiency director.  Edward Randolph, Director of the Energy Division, joined by telephone.  Litteneker discussed Rule 23 issues and other relevant matters. Gaspari stated that the statewide CPUC-approved loan program administered by the California Alternative Energy and Advanced Transportation Financing Authority is also an appropriate vehicle for MCE's proposed programs. Berman stated that the fastest resolution could be the contract amendment approach that PG&E had proposed to MCE.

The oral communication will take place by Webex on February 21, 2024, at 2:00 p.m. to 2:30 p.m. with Nick Dalhberg, Energy Advisor to President Alice Busching Reynolds. SDCPs participants in this meeting will include: Alissa Greenwald, Associate Attorney, Keyes & Fox LLP;  Sheena  Tran,  Senior  Program  Manager, SDCP;  Aisha  Cervantes-Cissna,  Senior  Policy Manager, SDCP;  Colin  Santulli,  Director  of  Programs, SDCP;  Rebeca  Appel,  Land  Use  and Environment Group Program Manager, County of San Diego; Brenda Garcia Millan, Land Use and  Environment  Group  Program  Manager,  County  of  San  Diego; and  Eden  Brukman,  Chief Sustainability Officer, County of San Diego. This meeting will discuss a recently filed Motion to form the San Diego Regional Energy Network (SDREN). SDCP and County staff wish to discuss the SDREN portfolio plan, recent Motion responses filed by parties on February 5th, and SDRENs reply to said responses which will be filed on February 15th.
